# Always Document

Documentation is a first-class requirement in this project, on par with "always use scripts." Every significant change must leave a clear trail that humans can follow.

## When to Document

Document after ANY of these:

- Script changes (new flags, modified behavior, bug fixes)
- Configuration changes (new settings, changed defaults, new override patterns)
- Architectural changes (new components, changed data flow, new patterns)
- New features or capabilities
- Bug fixes (what was wrong, what was fixed, why)
- Workflow changes (new steps, changed procedures)
- Session work with significant changes (summarize what and why)

## What to Document

### For Script Changes
- Update the script's header comment block
- Update `docs/scripts.md` if the script's purpose or interface changed
- Update `docs/quick-reference.md` if `up.sh`/`down.sh` flags changed

### For Configuration Changes
- Update `docs/baseline-configuration.md` with the new configuration state
- Add inline YAML comments explaining non-obvious settings

### For Architectural Changes
- Update `docs/architecture.md` with the new design
- Update `README.md` if the high-level description changed

### For New Workflows
- Add to `docs/quick-reference.md`
- Consider adding to the `rhdh-local-task-recipes` skill (`.cursor/skills/rhdh-local-task-recipes/SKILL.md`)

### For Session Work
- Use clear, descriptive commit messages explaining "why" not just "what"
- For multi-step changes, summarize the overall goal and approach

## Where Documentation Lives

- `README.md` -- Getting started guide (update for high-level changes)
- `docs/architecture.md` -- System design, copy-sync pattern (update for architectural changes)
- `docs/scripts.md` -- up.sh/down.sh/backup.sh reference (update for script changes)
- `docs/quick-reference.md` -- Command cheat sheet (update for new commands or workflows)
- `docs/backup.md` -- Backup/restore guide (update for backup system changes)
- `docs/customization-guide.md` -- How to customize RHDH (update for customization system changes)
- `docs/baseline-configuration.md` -- Current config state (update for configuration changes)
- `docs/testing.md` -- Testing workflows (update for test procedure changes)
- `docs/jenkins-integration.md` -- Jenkins CI/CD setup (update for Jenkins changes)
- `rhdh-customizations/README.md` -- Customization directory guide
- `rhdh-local/docs/rhdh-local-guide/` -- TechDocs in MkDocs format (update for official feature docs)

## Documentation Quality Standards

- Use "copy-sync" terminology, NOT "symlinks" (the system copies files, not creates symlinks)
- Explain the "why" behind decisions, not just the "what"
- Keep examples current and tested
- Maintain consistency across documents (same terms, same procedures)

## Anti-Patterns

- NEVER leave a change undocumented
- NEVER assume the next person (human or AI) knows what you did
- NEVER update code without updating the corresponding documentation
- NEVER create new scripts or workflows without documenting them
